            "abstractNote": "We document the pollination biology and mating systems of\n              Neobuxbaumia mezcalaensis\n              and\n              Neobuxbaumia macrocephala,\n              two Mexican giant columnar cacti. These two species form mixed forests in the western Tehuacan Valley, Mexico. The flowers of both\n              N. mezcalaensis\n              and\n              N. macrocephala\n              exhibit nocturnal anthesis, are self‐incompatible, and are pollinated primarily by three species of nectar‐feeding bats (\n              Choeronycteris mexicana, Leptonycteris curasoae,\n              and\n              Leptonycteris nivalis\n              )\n              . Neobuxbaumia mezcalaensis\n              is androdioecious, a breeding system that appears to be uncommon among Cactaceae.\n              Neobuxbaumia macrocephala\n              is hermaphroditic. We hypothesize that columnar cacti show a geographical dichotomy in floral biology specialization that probably can be related to predictability in pollinator abundance.",
